(ι) The true dative expresses the person to or sor whom something is done, as for instance with verbs of giving, siem· ing, hoping, growing, etc., in Sanskrit, Latin, and Greek. This requires no illustration. It also stands with nouns of meaning similar to these verbs, e. g. ἐχθρός, φίλος, amr'cus, etc., and with substantives in δῶρα τοῖς θεοῖς, etc.

A dative is used in Greek in a predicative sense with εἰμι’, γίγνεσθαι, ὑπάρχειν, e. g. βουλομένῳ μοι’ ἔστιν, etc. This dative in the case of nouus denoting things is in Greek very rare, though common in Latin, eg. praesidio esre. In Greek the infinitive takes its place (p. 146).
